bubble plot

j =1
jac_plot = list()  # Initialize list to store plots

# Loop to create two plots: TSK to Stromal and Stromal to TSK
for (i in 1:2) {
  if (i == 1) {
    # Subset for TSK to Stromal communication
    communication_data = subsetCommunication(
      cc_list[[j]], 
      slot.name = "net",
      sources.use = "TSK",
      targets.use = c("Endothelial", "Fibroblast"),
      pairLR.use = NULL,
      thresh = 0.05
    )
    title_name = "TSK to Stromal"
  } else {
    # Subset for Stromal to TSK communication
    communication_data = subsetCommunication(
      cc_list[[i]], 
      slot.name = "net",
      sources.use = c("Endothelial", "Fibroblast"),
      targets.use = "TSK",
      pairLR.use = NULL,
      thresh = 0.05
    )
    title_name = "Stromal to TSK"
  }
  
  # Prepare data for plotting
  data = data.frame(
    x = factor(communication_data[, 3], levels = sort(unique(communication_data[, 3]))),
    y = factor(communication_data[, 4], levels = sort(unique(communication_data[, 4]))),
    Ratio = communication_data[, 5],
    Shape = paste0(communication_data$source, "-", communication_data$target)
  )
  
  # Generate plot
  jac_plot[[i]] = ggplot(data, aes(x = y, y = x, size = Ratio, color = Ratio)) +
    geom_point(aes(shape = Shape),  size = 3) +
    theme_light() +
    labs(y = "", x = "", color = "Probability", size = "Probability", title = title_name) +
    theme(
      axis.text.x = element_text(size = 8, angle = 45, hjust = 1),
      axis.text.y = element_text(size = 8),
      plot.title = element_text(size = 8, hjust = 0.5)
    ) +
    scale_color_viridis_c()
  
  # Print the plot; helpful when running in a loop to force plot rendering
  print(jac_plot[[i]])
}

# This line is optional, prints the list of plots if you need to access them later

                          names(cell_lable_sec_cc[cell_lable_sec_cc%in% "Fibroblast"])]
